SUMMARY:Macroeconomics – Daniele Coen-Pirani (Pittsburgh) – Do Mergers 
 Increase Markups? Evidence from U.S. Public Firms joint with Hokyu Song.
LOCATION:Room 304\, FBE Building\, 111 Barry St\, Carlton VIC 3053
DESCRIPTION:Daniele Coen-Pirani: “Do Mergers Increase Markups? Evidence f
 rom U.S. Public Firms joint with Hokyu Song.”\nhttps://sites.google.com/
 view/danielecoenpirani/home\n\nZoom: https://unimelb.zoom.us/j/84055677057
 ?pwd=q1KyfcUkOWfMfEThCYsc9fs2jh2vCa.1&from=addon\n\nGoogle Maps: https://m
 aps.app.goo.gl/BirLkJKurX9pSbBB8\n\nABSTRACT:\nWe empirically investigate 
 the impact of mergers and acquisitions (M&As) on firm-level markups\, prof
 itability\, and productivity using data from Compustat for U.S. publicly t
 raded firms and the complete set of U.S. domestic M&A deals from 1985 to 2
 019. The analysis relies on event studies and robust difference-in-differe
 nces approaches with staggered adoption. By focusing on the impact of merg
 ers within narrow industry groups\, we ensure that the estimated effects o
 n markups are independent of the production function parameters required t
 o measure markup levels. Our results show that M&As lead to small but stat
 istically significant declines in acquirers’ markups. However\, mergers 
 also result in higher profit rates for acquirers\, driven by a reduction i
 n the relative importance of fixed costs and capital rental payments compa
 red to sales. Finally\, we find that mergers have no significant effect on
  labor productivity.
URL:https://unimelb.zoom.us/j/84055677057?pwd=q1KyfcUkOWfMfEThCYsc9fs2jh2vC
 a.1&from=addon
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:181f05f24b3413c8bb81a6b6d9d85ceb@generated
DTSTAMP:20260319T140831Z
LAST-MODIFIED:20260319T140831Z
SEQUENCE:0
DTSTART;TZID=Australia/Melbourne:20260326T120000
DTEND;TZID=Australia/Melbourne:20260326T131500
SUMMARY:Macroeconomics – Woan Foong Wong (Oregon) – Foreign Dependence 
 in Global Shipping
LOCATION:Room 404\, FBE Building\, 111 Barry St\, Carlton VIC 3053
DESCRIPTION:Woan Foong Wong: “Foreign Dependence in Global Shipping”\nh
 ttps://sites.google.com/site/wongwoanfoong/home\n\nZoom: https://unimelb.z
 oom.us/j/84055677057?pwd=q1KyfcUkOWfMfEThCYsc9fs2jh2vCa.1&from=addon\n\nGo
 ogle Maps: https://maps.app.goo.gl/BirLkJKurX9pSbBB8\n\nABSTRACT:\nWe stud
 y countries' dependence on foreign-built and foreign-operated containershi
 ps\, the vulnerability this dependence creates to shipping and geopolitica
 l disruptions\, and the potential for policy to mitigate these risks. We d
 ocument that global shipbuilding is highly concentrated in China and South
  Korea\, with South Korea specializing in larger vessels and China account
 ing for a growing share of newer capacity. In contrast\, vessel operation 
 is substantially more dispersed: most Chinese-built ships are operated by 
 non-Chinese carriers\, highlighting the deep integration of Chinese-built 
 capacity into global shipping networks. Using ship-level registry data mat
 ched to the universe of U.S. import shipments\, we show that the United St
 ates mirrors this global structure: U.S. trade relies overwhelmingly on ve
 ssels from East Asia while the operators serving U.S. routes are considera
 bly more diversified. To quantify how such dependence shapes trade costs a
 nd vulnerability\, we develop a quantitative shipping model with endogenou
 s fleet investment\, rental markets\, route assembly by operators\, and sp
 atial general equilibrium trade. The framework provides a tractable mappin
 g from fleet specific shocks\, whether arising from geopolitical disruptio
 ns or policy interventions\, to shipping prices\, routing patterns\, bilat
 eral trade costs\, and aggregate welfare. By combining observed exposure t
 o different fleets with shipping cost shares and trade patterns\, the mode
 l allows us to evaluate how disruptions propagate and how policies that ta
 rget particular fleets reshape trade outcomes in equilibrium. Applied to r
 ecent Section 301 style surcharges\, the model implies welfare losses conc
 entrated on highly exposed routes\, with additional spillovers operating t
 hrough fleet substitution and routing adjustment.
URL:https://unimelb.zoom.us/j/84055677057?pwd=q1KyfcUkOWfMfEThCYsc9fs2jh2vC
 a.1&from=addon
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:7630bb74b3fbc68a97446c029cee7ff9@generated
DTSTAMP:20260319T140831Z
LAST-MODIFIED:20260319T140831Z
SEQUENCE:0
DTSTART;TZID=Australia/Melbourne:20260402T120000
DTEND;TZID=Australia/Melbourne:20260402T131500
SUMMARY:Macroeconomics – James Graham (Sydney) – Monetary Policy and th
 e Homeownership Rate
LOCATION:Room 404\, FBE Building\, 111 Barry St\, Carlton VIC 3053
DESCRIPTION:James Graham: “Monetary Policy and the Homeownership Rate”\
 nhttps://www.jamesandrewgraham.com/\n\nZoom: https://unimelb.zoom.us/j/840
 55677057?pwd=q1KyfcUkOWfMfEThCYsc9fs2jh2vCa.1&from=addon\n\nGoogle Maps: h
 ttps://maps.app.goo.gl/BirLkJKurX9pSbBB8\n\nABSTRACT:\nHow does monetary p
 olicy affect homeownership? A monetary contraction may have contrasting ef
 fects due to rising interest rates\, falling incomes\, and lower house pri
 ces. To investigate\, we build a high-frequency heterogeneous household li
 fe-cycle model with housing tenure decisions\, mortgage finance\, and an e
 xogenous stochastic  process to capture macroeconomic dynamics following a
  monetary policy shock. A monetary contraction reduces homeownership\, wit
 h the initial impact driven by rising mortgage rates and persistent effect
 s due to lower household incomes. Ownership dynamics are shaped by mortgag
 e borrowing constraints\, property taxes\, macroeconomic conditions\, and 
 household expectations about monetary policy. Finally\, a monetary contrac
 tion is associated with welfare losses that are heavily concentrated among
  potential home buyers.
URL:https://unimelb.zoom.us/j/84055677057?pwd=q1KyfcUkOWfMfEThCYsc9fs2jh2vC
 a.1&from=addon
END:VEVENT
