SUMMARY:PhD Brown Bag Seminar – Eungwon Lee (University of Melbourne) –
  A Two-period Imperfect Mortgage Pricing Model
LOCATION:Room 304\, FBE Building\, 111 Barry St\, Carlton VIC 3053
DESCRIPTION:Eungwon Lee: “A Two-period Imperfect Mortgage Pricing Model
 ”\n\nGoogle Maps: https://maps.app.goo.gl/BirLkJKurX9pSbBB8\n\nABSTRACT:
 \nWe characterise equilibrium mortgage choice and pricing for defaultable\
 , non-recourse mortgages in a two-period model with a binary house-value s
 hock. Limited liability implies two endogenous regimes: households either 
 repay in all states or walk away in the bad state by giving up the collate
 ral. We show there is a unique cutoff in mortgage prices: below the cutoff
  (tight borrowing terms) households choose lower leverage and repay\, wher
 eas above the cutoff (loose terms) they take higher leverage and default i
 n the bad state. We embed this household block into a Cournot mortgage mar
 ket where a finite number of banks compete with an exogenous cost of funds
 . In each regime\, a unique symmetric equilibrium pricing exists. Greater 
 competition makes mortgage cheaper but can also shift the equilibrium from
  repayment to default rather than simply improving borrowing conditions. C
 onsequently\, some market power can be stabilising. With lump-sum profit r
 ebates welfare is maximised at an interior level of competition.
END:VEVENT
