SUMMARY:PhD Brown Bag Seminar – Landi Lin (University of Melbourne) – W
 hat factors determine the termination of BITs
LOCATION:Room 304\, FBE Building\, 111 Barry St\, Carlton VIC 3053
DESCRIPTION:Landi Lin: “What factors determine the termination of BITs”
 \n\nGoogle Maps: https://maps.app.goo.gl/BirLkJKurX9pSbBB8\n\nABSTRACT:\nT
 he determinants of bilateral investment treaty (BIT) formation are well un
 derstood\, but the recent wave of treaty terminations remains largely unex
 plained. I develop a two-period model in which a host country decides whet
 her to maintain or exit an existing BIT. The decision is shaped by three f
 orces: exit costs\, dispute loss under investor–state dispute settlement
 \, and policy constraints imposed by the treaty. The government trades off
  the value of policy flexibility against expected dispute losses and the f
 ixed cost of withdrawal. The model implies that termination becomes more o
 ptimal when treaty constraints are sufficiently binding\, dispute loss is 
 high\, or exit costs are low. These results provide a simple theoretical e
 xplanation for the recent increase in BIT terminations.
END:VEVENT
